																						Tweedy-Holmes
										</a>
																	</div>
																								</figcaption>
							</div>
			</div>
</figure>
</p>

<p><strong><span class="large">I scheduled</span></strong> time off from work to attend my brother&rsquo;s trial. Someone had to be there to make sure he didn&rsquo;t deliver a stupefying speech or go berserk when they sent him to jail.</p>

<p>But the <span class="smallcaps">DA</span> and Smoke&rsquo;s attorney met at the eleventh hour to discuss one last plea-bargain possibility.</p>

<p>&ldquo;My attorney says it&rsquo;s called &lsquo;diversion,&rsquo;&nbsp;&rdquo; Smoke told me on the phone. &ldquo;I agree to a fine and some community service, and the charge is knocked down to a misdemeanor.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;No trial?&rdquo; I asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; Smoke answered, &ldquo;but it&rsquo;s still bullshit, because I didn&rsquo;t do anything wrong!&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Take the deal!&rdquo; I screamed at my brother.</p>

<p>Reluctantly he did, and afterward he finally told our father about the arrest.</p>

<p>&ldquo;What did Dad say?&rdquo; I asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Well,&rdquo; Smoke inhaled on a cigarette, &ldquo;he was pissed, of course, because he said he could&rsquo;ve helped. Something about knowing the sheriff.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The fifteen-hundred-dollar fine hurt Smoke more than the five hundred hours of community service. But a preacher cousin of ours gave him a job painting the old family church, and somehow that led to Smoke&rsquo;s becoming choir director and &ldquo;performing&rdquo; at the summer&rsquo;s last revival meeting.</p>

<p>The tiny rural congregation sat silent (and perhaps stunned) as Smoke opened with an old Bob Dylan song titled &ldquo;When the Ship Comes In.&rdquo; Ostensibly it&rsquo;s about the Second Coming, but it&rsquo;s packed with the kind of payback my brother dreams of:</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh the foes will rise / With the sleep still in their eyes / And they&rsquo;ll jerk from their beds and think they&rsquo;re / dreamin&rsquo;. / But they&rsquo;ll pinch themselves and squeal / And know that it&rsquo;s for real, / The hour when the ship comes in.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Harmonica solo.</p>

<p>While waiting on that ship, Smoke filed a multi-million-dollar lawsuit against the little detective.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Someone&rsquo;s gotta stand up to that bastard,&rdquo; he told me on the phone.</p>

<p>He&rsquo;d also enrolled in community college, he said. He had his sights set on a job teaching high-school biology and coaching baseball. I could hear the television on in the background.</p>

<p>&ldquo;What are you watching?&rdquo; I asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;<em>Dragnet.</em>&rdquo; Smoke exhaled. &ldquo;Joe Friday&rsquo;s still an asshole.&rdquo;</p>
														</div>


				
